%N A395563 Indices of 2 in A395473: Number k such that Q(chi) takes 2 different fields for chi running through the Dirichlet characters modulo k, where Q(chi) is the field generated by the values of chi.
%C A395563 Numbers k such that psi(k) = 2*p for some prime p.
%C A395563 Numbers that divide 240 or 504 but not 24, and numbers of the form d*q for some safe prime q and d | 24.
%C A395563 Occurrences of 4 consecutive numbers other than (20, 21, 22, 23) are congruent to (716, 717, 718, 719) (mod 720), generated by some prime p == 89 (mod 90).
%C A395563 Proof: Suppose that (d1*p1, d2*p2, d3*p3, d4*p4) are 4 consecutive members in A395563, i.e., d1, d2, d3, d4 are divisors of 24, and p1, p2, p3, p4 are safe primes != 7. We note that pi == 5 (mod 6), so none of the four di*pi can be congruent to 1 modulo 6. As a result, these four numbers are congruent to either (2, 3, 4, 5) or (3, 4, 5, 0) modulo 6.
%C A395563 If (d1*p1, d2*p2, d3*p3, d4*p4) == (3, 4, 5, 0) (mod 6), then d1 = 3, d2 = 2 (mod 6), d3 = 1, d4 == 0 (mod 6). It follows that d1*p1 == 15 (mod 18), so d4*p4 == 0 (mod 18), but this is impossible since it would imply d4 == 0 (mod 18).
%C A395563 If (d1*p1, d2*p2, d3*p3, d4*p4) == (2, 3, 4, 5) (mod 6), then d1 == 4 (mod 6), d2 = 3, d3 == 2 (mod 6), d4 = 1. Of course only one (and exactly one) of d1 and d3 is divisible by 4, so (d1, d2, d3, d4) = (4, 3, 2, 1). Write p1 = 2*p + 1 for some prime p, then p2 = (8*p + 5)/3, (p2 - 1)/2 = (4*p + 1)/3, p3 = 4*p + 3, p4 = 8*p + 7, and these must be all primes. Taking modulo 3 and 5 yields p == 89 (mod 90) if p > 2.
%H A395563 Jianing Song, <a href="/A395563/b395563.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%H A395563 Wikipedia, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dirichlet_character">Dirichlet character</a>.
%t A395563 PositionIndex[DivisorSigma[0, CarmichaelLambda[Range[1000]]/2]][2] (* _Paolo Xausa_, Jun 03 2026 *)
%t A395563 (* Alternative, after PARI: *)
%t A395563 A395563Q[k_] := ((Divisible[240, k] || Divisible[504, k]) && !Divisible[24, k]) || (PrimeQ[#] && PrimeQ[(#-1)/2] & [k/GCD[k, 24]]);
%t A395563 Select[Range[1000], A395563Q] (* _Paolo Xausa_, Jun 03 2026 *)
%o A395563 (PARI) isA395563(n) = if((240%n==0 || 504%n==0) && 24%n!=0, return(1)); n = n/gcd(24,n); return(isprime(n) && isprime((n-1)/2))
%Y A395563 Cf. A395473, A018253, A395464, A005385 (safe primes).
%Y A395563 Cf. A396495 (primes p such that (8*p+4, 8*p+5, 8*p+6, 8*p+7) are four consecutive terms), A396497 (k such that 720*k-4, 720*k-3, 720*k-2, 720*k-1 are four consecutive trems).
